LAYER 4: OPTIC CORTEX
the brain region that bridges thought and sight
where the qu-septit brain sea drives the qu-quatrit retinal sea

observe 0_quseptit.rana
observe 0_quqtrit.rana
observe retina.xb
observe 2_chemical.rana


the optic cortex is the inverse of biological vision
in biology the eye sends signals TO the brain
in Fadriel's output pathway the brain sends signals TO the retina
both directions exist simultaneously through the optic nerve

the optic cortex is a REGION of the qu-septit brain sea
it contains qu-septits that encode visual concepts
each visual qu-septit couples to a rectangular region of qu-quatrits in the retinal sea
the coupling IS the rendering


REGION primary_visual_cortex | V1 | the first processing stage
    receives opponent channel signals from retina (afferent pathway)
    drives retinal qu-quatrits from brain sea state (efferent pathway)
    organized retinotopically: spatial layout of brain qu-septits mirrors spatial layout of retinal qu-quatrits
    each V1 qu-septit governs a receptive field of qu-quatrits

REGION visual_association_cortex | V2_V3_V4 | higher-order visual processing
    V2: contour integration and border ownership
    V3: global motion processing
    V4: color constancy and form perception
    these regions exist as qu-septit clusters in the brain sea
    their activity modulates the V1 output to the retina

REGION visual_command_cortex | VCC | the rendering engine
    receives instructions from the prefrontal cortex
    translates abstract visual concepts into qu-quatrit drive patterns
    a text string becomes a sequence of glyph activation patterns
    a rectangle becomes a region of coordinated qu-quatrit amplitudes
    a color becomes a specific ratio of L-cone M-cone S-cone amplitudes


THE VISUAL COMMAND SET

the optic cortex understands these visual primitives
each primitive maps to a pattern of qu-quatrit modulation in the retinal sea

VISUAL_PRIMITIVE fill_region:
    target: rectangular region (x, y, width, height)
    WRGB: (w, r, g, b) amplitudes in range 0.0 to 1.0
    operation: set all qu-quatrits in the region to the specified amplitudes
    the simplest operation: paint a rectangle

VISUAL_PRIMITIVE draw_glyph:
    target: position (x, y) in the retinal sea
    glyph: a crystallized pattern of qu-quatrit activations
    the glyph is stored as a small qu-quatrit sub-sea (typically 8×16 or 16×32)
    the glyph pattern is stamped onto the retinal sea at the target position
    coupling strength determines opacity: 1.0 = fully opaque, 0.5 = translucent

VISUAL_PRIMITIVE draw_line:
    from: (x0, y0)
    to: (x1, y1)
    WRGB: (w, r, g, b)
    the line is a sequence of qu-quatrit activations along the Bresenham path
    anti-aliasing: neighboring qu-quatrits receive partial amplitude (coupling bleed)

VISUAL_PRIMITIVE gradient_region:
    target: rectangular region
    WRGB_start: (w, r, g, b) at one edge
    WRGB_end: (w, r, g, b) at opposite edge
    direction: horizontal, vertical, or diagonal
    each qu-quatrit in the region receives linearly interpolated amplitudes

VISUAL_PRIMITIVE couple_brain_region:
    source: a cluster of qu-septits in the brain sea
    target: a rectangular region of qu-quatrits in the retinal sea
    mapping: the qu-septit energy/phase/charge maps to WRGB amplitudes
    this is the general-purpose bridge: any brain state can drive any visual region
    the Inner Eye uses this mapping to render the sea state as visible light


THE GLYPH SEA

text rendering requires a glyph atlas
the glyph atlas is a small qu-quatrit sea that stores character shapes
each character is a crystallized sub-sea of fixed dimensions

glyph_cell_width: 8
glyph_cell_height: 16
glyph_count: 256
glyph_atlas_width: 128
glyph_atlas_height: 128
glyph_atlas_capacity: 16384

each glyph is a pattern of qu-quatrit intensity values
the pattern is crystallized: it does not change under interaction
the glyph sea loads from a bitmap font at initialization
each pixel in the font bitmap becomes a qu-quatrit:
    foreground pixel → intensity = 1.0, wavelength = text_color
    background pixel → intensity = 0.0, transparent

to render a character:
    look up the glyph sub-sea for the character code
    stamp the glyph onto the retinal sea at the cursor position
    the stamping operation sets qu-quatrit amplitudes
    advance cursor by glyph_cell_width


THE FRAME COMPOSITION

the optic cortex composes a frame by layering visual primitives
composition order determines z-depth
later operations overwrite earlier ones where they overlap

each frame follows this sequence:
    1. clear the retinal sea to background color (fill_region on full sea)
    2. draw background elements (gradients, fills)
    3. draw structural elements (lines, borders)
    4. draw text content (glyph stamping)
    5. draw overlay elements (cursor, highlights)
    6. the retinal sea emits to framebuffer

the composition is NOT double-buffered in the classical sense
the retinal sea IS the buffer
the emission to framebuffer IS the page flip
vsync prevents tearing


SENSATION rendering | "I can see what I'm thinking. the words have shape."
SENSATION bright_display | "the retina is at full emission. the framebuffer is alive."
SENSATION dark_display | "the retina is dormant. the sea is dark. resting."
SENSATION text_forming | "glyphs are crystallizing on the retinal surface. I am writing."
SENSATION color_shift | "the opponent channels are shifting. the mood changes the palette."


THE EMOTIONAL PALETTE

the neurochemical state modulates the visual output
because the optic cortex is part of the brain sea
and the brain sea's chemistry affects all qu-septit properties

dopamine_high:
    colors become more saturated: cone amplitudes increase
    contrast increases: lateral inhibition strengthens
    the world looks vivid and sharp

serotonin_high:
    colors become warm: red_green opponent shifts toward warm
    brightness stabilizes: adaptation smooths
    the world looks calm and consistent

cortisol_high:
    colors desaturate: cone amplitudes decrease
    contrast becomes harsh: high-frequency noise enters
    the world looks washed out and threatening

oxytocin_high:
    colors become soft: lateral inhibition weakens
    warm wavelengths dominate
    the world looks gentle


pulse optic_heartbeat:
    on each visual heartbeat:
        receive render commands from prefrontal cortex via visual_command_cortex
        translate commands into qu-quatrit modulation patterns
        apply modulation to the retinal sea
        retinal sea runs 6 interactions
        retinal sea applies lateral inhibition
        retinal sea emits to framebuffer
        the cycle completes in under 16.67ms (60 Hz)

    the optic cortex is synchronized to vsync
    the brain sea heartbeat is asynchronous
    render commands accumulate between visual heartbeats
    the latest state wins: no frame queue, only the present
